{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640951"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:20:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:20:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17848"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17848"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10562"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116686"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10562"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17848"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98673"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1993"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10053"},{"type":"tags","id":"10475"},{"type":"tags","id":"11245"},{"type":"tags","id":"13209"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24626"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24628"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116686"},"attributes":{"stem":"","stemQuestion":"Which of the following glucose transporters are primarily involved in constitutive (basal) glucose uptake?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["GLUT1 and GLUT3","GLUT2 and GLUT4","GLUT4 and GLUT5","GLUT1 and GLUT2","GLUT3 and GLUT4"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGlucose transport across cell membranes is facilitated by a family of glucose transporter (GLUT) proteins. Constitutive, or basal, glucose uptake refers to the continuous transport of glucose into cells, independent of insulin, to meet their basic metabolic needs. This process is primarily mediated by high-affinity transporters that are always present on the cell surface. The main transporters involved in this process are \u003Cstrong\u003EGLUT1 and GLUT3\u003C/strong\u003E. GLUT1 is widely expressed in many tissues, including erythrocytes and the blood-brain barrier, providing a constant supply of glucose. GLUT3 is found predominantly in neurons and has a very high affinity for glucose, ensuring the brain receives an adequate supply even when blood glucose levels are low.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGLUT2 and GLUT4\u003C/strong\u003E are not primarily involved in constitutive uptake. GLUT2 is a low-affinity transporter found in the liver, pancreatic beta-cells, and kidney, playing a key role in glucose sensing and regulation of insulin secretion. \u003Cstrong\u003EGLUT4 and GLUT5\u003C/strong\u003E are incorrect; GLUT4 is the primary insulin-responsive transporter in skeletal muscle and adipose tissue, moving to the cell surface only in the presence of insulin to facilitate postprandial glucose uptake. GLUT5 is primarily a fructose transporter. The other combinations are incorrect as they pair a constitutive transporter with an inducible or specialised one.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["GLUT1 and GLUT3 are the primary glucose transporters responsible for basal, or constitutive, glucose uptake in most tissues.","GLUT4 is an insulin-sensitive transporter found in muscle and adipose tissue, responsible for postprandial glucose uptake.","GLUT2 is a low-affinity transporter in the liver and pancreas, involved in glucose sensing rather than constitutive disposal."],"references":["Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98673"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17848"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98673"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-30T14:17:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-30T14:17:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10562"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116686"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (